    "content_hash": "sha256:670a7768f1c220b0af01305b16b5e7233e1f49cc33c601eab4aab1b71d4f47c6",
    "summary": "Nefertiti was the Great Royal Wife of the [[event:1805|Akhenaten]], pharaoh of the [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]], who reigned during the [[event:1804|Amarna Period]] approximately 1353–1336 BC. She played a prominent and unusually public role in the religious revolution that Akhenaten promoted, which centered on the exclusive veneration of the Aten, the sun disc. Representations of Nefertiti in Amarna art are notably egalitarian in scale compared to those of earlier Egyptian queens, and she appears alongside her husband in ritual and public contexts that suggest she held exceptional religious and possibly political authority.\n\nNefertiti is best known today through the famous painted limestone bust discovered at the sculptor Thutmose's workshop at Amarna in 1912 and now housed in the Neues Museum in Berlin. This bust, with its elegant elongated neck, fine features, and distinctive flat-topped blue crown, has become one of the most recognizable images from the ancient world and a symbol of ancient Egyptian artistry. The bust was probably a sculptor's model used for training apprentices to render the queen's likeness consistently.\n\nThe fate of Nefertiti after the twelfth year of Akhenaten's reign remains uncertain. She disappears from the official record around that time, and scholars debate whether she died, fell from favor, or — as some evidence suggests — assumed the role of co-regent under a different name. Some Egyptologists have proposed that she ruled as pharaoh Neferneferuaten after Akhenaten's death, before [[event:1806|Tutankhamun]] came to the throne. Her mummy has not been definitively identified, though candidates among unidentified royal mummies continue to be examined with new forensic techniques.",
